# Accepted historical findings — DO NOT use this file for new leaks.
#
# Each line is a gitleaks fingerprint of the form
#   <commit-sha>:<path>:<rule-id>:<line-number>
# that the scanner should treat as already-reviewed.
#
# This file exists for one reason only: gitleaks scans the *full git
# history* on every CI run, so a credential that was leaked in the past
# (even if it has since been rotated, removed from the working tree, and
# .gitignored) will keep tripping the scan forever unless the commit is
# rewritten out of `main`. Rewriting `main`'s history is operator-owned
# and politically expensive (force-push, every fork must reclone, GitHub
# Actions cache invalidation, etc.) — see the v0.7.32 post-mortem in
# `replit.md`. Until that cleanup happens, listing the exact historical
# fingerprints here keeps the CI gate green for *new* commits while
# leaving the rules themselves armed.
#
# Adding a new line here REQUIRES a comment explaining why. If a new
# credential ends up in a commit, the answer is almost always "rotate
# the key, remove the value from the file, and re-commit" — NOT "add a
# fingerprint here". This file should be append-only for genuine
# historical leaks, not a way to silence inconvenient findings.

